eving something meaningful.\n\n- Clayton M. Christensen, How Will You Measure Your Life?\n|\nPublication is a marathon, not a sprint. Writing the book is only the start.\n\n- Jo\n|\nWell, thanks for not shooting anyone, I guess', said Marcus. 'My contribution was to somehow refrain from peeing myself. You can thank me later.\n\n- Dan Wells, Partials\n|\nIt has become much harder, in the past century, to tell where the garden leaves off and pure nature begins.\n\n- Michael Pollan, The Botany of Desire: A Plant's-Eye View of the World\n|\nYou must not only pray and fast, but read and mediate on word of God.\n\n- Lailah Gifty Akita, Think Great: Be Great!\n|\nNo one knows for certain how much impact they have on the lives of other people. Oftentimes, we have no clue. Yet we push it just the same.\n\n- Jay Asher, Thirteen Reasons Why\n|\nBy sharing, we express our gratitude for abundance and create emptiness for receiving.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nYou have to, take a deep breath. and allow the music to flow through you. Revel in it, allow yourself to awe. When you play allow the music to break your heart with its beauty.\n\n- Kelly\n|\nIn the midst of compassion, we find ourselves. We discover our true purpose.\n\n- Jana\n|\nThere were about seventy-nine squillion people in the world, and if you were very lucky, you would end up being loved by fifteen or twenty of them.\n\n- Nick Hornby, About a Boy\n|\nTake care, take care. This city thrives! It's money gives you wings to soar. But it is a yoke on your shoulders and you would do well to take note of the bruise around your neck.\n\n- Jessie Burton, The Miniaturist\n|\nI have an attraction to strangeand unusual things.I find them interesting,spellbinding,utterly fascinating.\n\n- Melody  Lee, Moon Gypsy\n|\nSee--two who dreamed that dream, and you were one.\n\n- Caris\n|\nA hoverfly is held in a sunbeam, an insect in amber.\n\n- Rob Cowen, Common Ground\n|\nTo see the years touch ye gives me joy', he whispered, 'for it means that ye live.\n\n- Diana\n|\nThe materialistic view of happiness of our age starkly revealed in our understanding of the word 'luxury.\n\n- Alain\n|\nAs for monkeys, I would have five, and they would be named: See No Evil, Hear No Evil, Speak No Evil, Do Pretty Much Whatever The Hell You Want, and Expensive Attorney.\n\n- Tad\n|\nWe have one hundred percent chance of achieving what God has called us to, even if we are starting from scratch\n\n- Sunday\n|\nMankind is a melody, every being around you is a note you have to mix in the right order in your life\n\n- Freedom\n|\nStopping, sitting down and finding time for reflection are considered to be the most essential action related to fulfilling a human’s destination\n\n- Sunday\n|\nHappiness is like a butterfly which, when pursued, is always beyond our grasp, but, if you will sit down quietly, may alight upon you.\n\n- Nathaniel\n|\nInstead of making decisions based on safety, security, or practicality, the Soul wants us to live our lives according to what we find to be most beautiful.\n\n- Elisa Romeo, Meet Your Soul: A Powerful Guide to Connect with Your Most Sacred Self\n|\nI think that's what you say when you can't have something you want, isn't it? You say you don't want it in the first place.\n\n- Jodi Lynn Anderson, Midnight at the Electric\n|\nAll is as if the world did cease to exist. The city's monuments go unseen, its past unheard, and its culture slowly fading in the dismal sea.\n\n- Nathan\n|\nGo and get your things,' he said. 'Dreams mean work.\n\n- Paulo Coelho, By the River Piedra I Sat Down and Wept\n|\nEven when you don't see Him working, He's busy working on your behalf. Forever grateful for God's grace!\n\n- Yvonne Pierre, The Day My Soul Cried:  A Memoir\n|\nTina leans forward and asks quietly, 'Do you? You know? Love her?'Squeezing Nat’s knee again, I reply, 'She’s teachin’ me how.\n\n- Belle Aurora, Love Thy Neighbour\n|\nDreams and restless thoughts came flowing to him from the river, from the t